<div id="hardin-was-wrong" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">01</span>Hardin was wrong</h2>
  <p>In 1968, Garrett Hardin published "The Tragedy of the Commons" in <em>Science</em>. The argument: any resource held in common will be inevitably destroyed, because each rational individual has an incentive to overuse it. The solution: privatize or regulate. The commons cannot govern itself.</p>
  <p>This became one of the most cited papers in environmental and economic policy. It provided the intellectual justification for enclosing fisheries, forests, and grazing lands that had been communally managed for generations. It was taught as established fact in economics courses worldwide.</p>
  <p>Hardin was describing a specific game-theoretic situation: anonymous individuals, no communication, no norms, no history. He wasn't describing actual commons governance. Ostrom noticed this, and spent her career studying what actual commons governance looked like.</p>
</div>

<div id="what-she-found" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">02</span>What she actually found</h2>
  <p>Ostrom and her collaborators studied hundreds of cases: irrigation systems in Spain and the Philippines that had operated continuously for centuries, Swiss mountain pastures governed by the same communities since the 13th century, Japanese forest commons managed sustainably across generations, fishing communities in Maine and Turkey.</p>
  <p>What they found: communities can and do govern shared resources sustainably without privatization or state control. Not always — some commons fail. But the ones that work share identifiable structural features. It's not that the commons is inherently stable or inherently fragile. It depends on how it's organized.</p>
  <div class="callout"><span class="callout-label">The core finding</span><p>The tragedy of the commons is not a law of nature. It's what happens when a commons lacks the institutional structures that make sustainable collective governance possible. Those structures can be built.</p></div>
</div>

<div id="design-principles" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">03</span>The eight design principles</h2>
  <p>From the cases that worked, Ostrom distilled eight design principles — structural features that distinguished sustainable commons from failing ones:</p>
  <ol>
    <li><strong>Clearly defined boundaries.</strong> Who has rights to use the resource, and what resource is being governed, must be clearly defined.</li>
    <li><strong>Rules fit local conditions.</strong> The rules governing use reflect the specific ecological and social conditions of that particular commons. Imported, generic rules don't work.</li>
    <li><strong>Collective choice arrangements.</strong> The people affected by the rules have meaningful participation in modifying them.</li>
    <li><strong>Monitoring.</strong> Someone monitors both the resource and user behavior — and the monitors are either users themselves or accountable to users.</li>
    <li><strong>Graduated sanctions.</strong> Users who violate rules face sanctions that are graduated — light for first offenses, heavier for repeat violations — and applied by users or their accountable agents.</li>
    <li><strong>Conflict resolution mechanisms.</strong> Users and their officials have access to low-cost, local mechanisms for resolving disputes.</li>
    <li><strong>Minimal recognition of rights.</strong> External governmental authorities recognize the right of users to organize their own governance.</li>
    <li><strong>Nested enterprises.</strong> For larger commons, governance is organized in multiple nested layers — local communities within larger coordinating structures.</li>
  </ol>
  <p>These aren't prescriptions. They're patterns that appeared, independently, across hundreds of cases in different cultures and centuries. They describe what sustainable commons governance actually looks like from the inside.</p>
</div>

<div id="what-it-means" class="thinker-section">
  <h2 class="section-head"><span class="section-num">04</span>What this means</h2>
  <p>Ostrom's work does two things for the argument this site is building.</p>
  <p>First, it closes the "human nature" objection. The tragedy of the commons isn't inevitable. It's a specific failure mode that happens under specific conditions — conditions that can be identified and changed. The commons can work. We have centuries of evidence.</p>
  <p>Second, it gives us a design vocabulary. When someone asks "how would a commons actually govern this?" — a watershed, a neighborhood, a piece of software infrastructure, a data set — Ostrom's principles provide a framework for thinking through what structures would need to be in place. Not a blueprint, because the principles require local adaptation. But a checklist of what questions to ask.</p>
  <p>The enclosure argument requires claiming the commons is inherently unworkable. Ostrom's empirical record makes that claim hard to maintain.</p>
</div>

